Q1. Using plotly, make a state choropleth map for the month of October. Choose a different color scale than we used in the class lecture. https://plotly.com/python/builtin-colorscales/. Output your image to an .html file [no need to upload this].

  • Note: you will need to load the files from lecture and be sure to join the state abbreviations DataFrame, just like in lecture. The reason for this is that plotly uses the state abbreviations to define geographic regions for the choropleth map.
In[]:
## Temperature data by state

# Read data, parse dates
df_state = pd.read_csv('lecture21_globaltemps_states.csv',parse_dates=['dt'])

# Make a month column
df_state['Month'] = df_state['dt'].dt.month

# Only keep the US States
df_state = df_state[df_state['Country'] == 'United States']

# Fix Georgia
df_state = df_state.replace('Georgia (State)', 'Georgia') 

# Drop NaNs
df_state = df_state.dropna()

# Logical indices: only data in October
states_Oct = df_state['Month']==10

# Use groupby to calculate average mean temperature in January by state
df_state_avg = df_state.loc[states_Oct,["State", "AverageTemperature"]].groupby("State", sort=True).mean()

# Remove state from index so it is an actual column
df_state_avg.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Rename columns for convenience/clarity
df_state_avg.rename(columns={"AverageTemperature": "Temp_Oct"},inplace=True)

# Convert from Celsius to Fahrenheit
df_state_avg["Temp_Oct"] = 9.0/5.0 * df_state_avg["Temp_Oct"] + 32.0

# Load the state abbreviation file
df_state_abbr = pd.read_csv('lecture21_states_abbr.csv')

# Merge with data
df_state_avg = pd.merge(left=df_state_avg, right=df_state_abbr, on="State", how="left")

## plotting with plotly
fig = px.choropleth(df_state_avg,
                    locations="Abbreviation",
                    locationmode = 'USA-states',
                    color="Temp_Oct", 
                    hover_name="State", 
                    scope='usa',
                    color_continuous_scale="Viridis")
fig.show()
In[]:
fig.write_html('Lecture21_q1.html')

Q2. Using plotly, make a global choropleth map for the month of March. Choose a different color scale than we used in the class lecture or from Q1. Output your image to an .html file [no need to upload this].

## Temperature data by country
# Read data, parse dates
df_country = pd.read_csv('lecture21_globaltemps_countries.csv',parse_dates=['dt'])

# Drop NaNs
df_country = df_country.dropna()

# Make a month column
df_country['Month'] = df_country['dt'].dt.month

# Fix some country names
df_country = df_country.replace(
   ['Denmark (Europe)', 'France (Europe)', 'Netherlands (Europe)', 'United Kingdom (Europe)'],
   ['Denmark', 'France', 'Netherlands', 'United Kingdom']) 

# Logical indices: only data in March
country_oct = df_country['Month']== 3

# Use groupby to calculate average mean temperature in July by country
df_country_avg = df_country.loc[country_oct,["Country","AverageTemperature"]].groupby("Country", sort=True).mean()

# Remove state from index so it is an actual column
df_country_avg.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Rename columns for convenience/clarity
df_country_avg.rename(columns={"AverageTemperature": "Temp_Mar"},inplace=True)

# Convert from Celsius to Fahrenheit
df_country_avg["Temp_Mar"] = 9.0/5.0 * df_country_avg["Temp_Mar"] + 32.0

fig2 = px.choropleth(df_country_avg,
                    locations="Country",
                    locationmode = 'country names',
                    color="Temp_Mar", 
                    hover_name="Country", 
                    color_continuous_scale="spectral_r")
fig2.show()
In[]:
fig2.write_html('Lecture21_q2.html')

Q4. It is difficult to convert the dates to np.datetime64 format because instead of month/day there are julian days. Use your python skills to extract the julian day values (the first value to the right of the year) and add them as an integer column in your Q1 DataFrame. Display the first 5 rows of your dataframe.

  • You might do this with a for loop where you use .split(':').
  • There is an alternative solution with pd.to_datetime and an explicit formatting string.
  • Either approach is fine
In[]:
## creating empty list
jday_list = []
## extracting julian day and appending it to list
for i in nav_crest['Date']:
    date_str = i.split(":")
    jday_str = date_str[1]
    jday_int = int(jday_str)
    jday_list.append(jday_int)

## adding list of julian days to df, displaying first 5 rows
nav_crest["Jday"] = jday_list
nav_crest.head()

Q7. Create a 3D surface map of 'lecture21_grid.grd'. Use a different colorscale than used in lecture, and add contours.

Note that this grd file has a simpler format than the one used in lecture in that it stores the longitude and latitude arrays directly.

In[]:
## reading in dataset
lecture21_grid = netcdf_dataset('lecture21_grid.grd')

# make figure
fig = go.Figure(data=[go.Surface(z=lecture21_grid['altitude'], x=lecture21_grid['lon'], y=lecture21_grid['lat'], colorscale='icefire')])

# add contours
fig.update_traces(contours_z=dict(show=True, usecolormap=True,project_z=True))

# update the layout
fig.update_layout(title='Topography Grid', 
                  autosize=False,width=800, height=600) # use this to change size

fig.show()
